421. patris Genio ‘to the Spirit of his father.' Genius was the spiritual part of any rational being, which after death was no longer called genius, being now numbered among the lares or manes. Ovid, however, here uses the word genius for

the spirit of the dead Anchises. 425. omine ab isto i.c. from that ill-omened neglect.

426. suburbanis. Cremation and burial of the dead took place outside the walls. Some of the great roads leading into Rome, notably the Via Appia, are lined with tombs. See the picture in Liddell's Rome, p. 169.
